Note:
Bash→HIR Translator - Translate Bash AST to HIR

This file provides translation from Bash Abstract Syntax Tree (AST)
to High-level Intermediate Representation (HIR) for universal language
translation through the Translation system.

Features:
- Complete Bash AST → HIR translation
- Preserves shell-specific semantics
- Command and pipeline translation
- Control structure translation
- Function definition translation
- Variable assignment and expansion translation
- Redirection translation

HIR Format:
- Dictionaries for structured data
- Lists for collections
- Preserves all semantic information for bidirectional translation

Dependencies:
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
- compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_core.runa (HIR operations)
- frontends/bash/bash_parser.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/hashtable.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================================
Note: List Join Operator Token Types
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Mirrors the bash lexer's token type constants for the four command-list
Note: join operators. AST_LIST_OPERATOR marker nodes (node type 7) carry one of
Note: these values in their value field; translate_list maps each to the
Note: canonical operator spelling recorded in the HIR "operators" list.

Constant AST_LIST_OPERATOR as Integer is 7        Note: List join operator marker node type
Constant TOKEN_PIPE_PIPE as Integer is 41         Note: ||
Constant TOKEN_AMP as Integer is 42               Note: &
Constant TOKEN_AMP_AMP as Integer is 43           Note: &&
Constant TOKEN_SEMICOLON as Integer is 44         Note: ;

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR Dictionary and List Operations (REAL IMPLEMENTATIONS)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
HIR nodes are represented as untyped hashtables keyed by string field
names ("type", "children", "command_name", etc.) and the bash frontend
needs a single entry point so callers do not have to know which hashtable
implementation is currently wired in. Wrapping the primitive lets the
HIR storage backend be swapped (e.g., from open-addressing to chaining)
without touching the dozens of frontend walkers that build HIR nodes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates directly to hashtable_create from the Dict primitive. Returns
the new hashtable handle as an Integer pointer; the caller takes
ownership and must release the dictionary via hashtable_destroy when the
HIR node is freed. No fields are pre-populated because HIR construction
fills keys lazily based on the node kind detected during walking.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_hir_dict" returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR dictionary using real hashtable

    @Reasoning:
    HIR uses dictionaries to represent structured data with key-value pairs.
    This uses the production hashtable implementation from collections.
    @End Reasoning

    Return proc hashtable_create from Dict
End Process

@Reasoning:
Mirror of create_hir_dict but for ordered sequences. HIR uses lists for
children, arguments, pipeline stages, and any other position-significant
collection; using the production list_create implementation gives us
amortised O(1) append and O(1) indexed access.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_list" returns Integer:
    Note: Create HIR list using real dynamic list

    Return proc list_create from List
End Process

@Reasoning:
Thin wrapper over hashtable_set so the bash frontend can use its own
domain vocabulary (set_dict_value reads more naturally than hashtable_set
in walker code) while still leveraging the production hashtable
implementation underneath. The wrapper is intentionally not inlined to
keep the universal-translation HIR helpers consistent across frontends.
@End Reasoning
Process called "set_dict_value" takes dict as Integer, key as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set dictionary value using real hashtable_set

    Return proc hashtable_set from Dict with dict, key, value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Thin alias over list_push. Named "append" rather than "push" because the
HIR walker code reads more naturally with "append to children" than
"push children". Identity behaviour is preserved by direct delegation.
@End Reasoning
Process called "list_append" takes list as Integer, item as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Append item to list using real list_push

    Return proc list_push from List with list, item
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reader counterpart to set_dict_value. The "string" in the name is a
convention reflecting that the value is interpreted as a string handle
at the call site; the underlying hashtable_get is type-agnostic.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_dict_string_value" takes dict as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get string value from dictionary using real hashtable_get

    Return proc hashtable_get from Dict with dict, key
End Process

@Reasoning:
Sibling of get_dict_string_value, kept distinct because the call sites
that retrieve nested HIR nodes prefer the explicit naming. The underlying
hashtable_get behaviour is identical; the distinction is documentation
not behaviour.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_dict_hir_value" takes dict as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get HIR value from dictionary using real hashtable_get

    Return proc hashtable_get from Dict with dict, key
End Process

@Reasoning:
Domain-specific alias for list_length used by the HIR walker. The "count"
naming matches how the walker code thinks about node children
(child_count) versus generic list operations elsewhere in the codebase.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_list_count" takes list as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get list count using real list_length

    Return proc list_length from List with list
End Process

@Reasoning:
Domain-specific alias over list_get. Used by the translation walkers
when extracting children; the wrapping keeps the bash-frontend code free
from primitive-list naming so future swap to a different storage shape
remains a local change.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_list_item" takes list as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get list item using real list_get

    Return proc list_get from List with list, index
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST → HIR Translation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The three AST atom kinds (word=51, string=52, number=53) all carry their
textual payload at offset 8 in the AST node; translating to HIR means
selecting the canonical HIR node_type tag for each. AST_WORD maps to
HIR "word" rather than "identifier" because bash words can be filenames,
glob patterns, or command names depending on position, and we preserve
that ambiguity in the HIR for downstream targets that may resolve it
differently. Returning the bare dict for unknown types preserves the
HIR shape so the dispatcher does not crash on novel AST kinds.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_word" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate word/string/number to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 0
    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 8

    Let hir_node be proc create_hir_dict

    Note: AST_WORD
    If node_type is equal to 51:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "node_type", "word"
        proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "value", value
        Return hir_node
    End If

    Note: AST_STRING
    If node_type is equal to 52:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "node_type", "string_literal"
        proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "value", value
        Return hir_node
    End If

    Note: AST_NUMBER
    If node_type is equal to 53:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "node_type", "number_literal"
        proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "value", value
        Return hir_node
    End If

    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bash variable references ($var, ${var}) carry only the name; the HIR
"variable_reference" node stores that name verbatim so the downstream
emitter can decide whether to render it as a load, a string expansion,
or a default-substitution depending on the target language's semantics.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_variable" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate variable reference to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 8

    Let hir_var be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_var, "node_type", "variable_reference"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_var, "name", value

    Return hir_var
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bash redirections (>, >>, <, 2>&1) appear in the AST as nodes whose
first child is the target. We model them in HIR as a "redirection" dict
with a target field; the bash parser already separates the redirection
operator from the target, so the operator details are recorded in the
AST node's attribute slots (not handled here in v0.0.8.5 - the emitter
side tracks operator preservation via metadata).
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_redirection" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate redirection to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 40

    Let hir_redirect be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_redirect, "node_type", "redirection"

    Note: Target (filename or file descriptor)
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let target_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let target_hir be proc translate_word with target_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_redirect, "target", target_hir
    End If

    Return hir_redirect
End Process

@Reasoning:
Simple commands in bash split children into the command name (always
first), the argument words, and any redirections interleaved between
them. The translator partitions children into argument and redirection
lists based on the child's AST kind (40 = AST_REDIRECTION) so both sets
are accessible as separate HIR fields. Indexing by 'i multiplied by 8'
reflects the v0.0.8.5 layout where children is a pointer table of 8-byte
slots.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_command" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate simple command to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 40

    Let hir_cmd be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_cmd, "node_type", "command"

    Note: Command name (first child)
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let cmd_name_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let cmd_name_hir be proc translate_word with cmd_name_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_cmd, "name", cmd_name_hir
    End If

    Note: Arguments and redirections
    Let args_list be proc create_hir_list
    Let redirects_list be proc create_hir_list

    Let i be 1  Note: Skip first child (command name)
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
        Let child_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child_ast, 0

        Note: Check if redirection (AST_REDIRECTION = 40)
        If child_type is equal to 40:
            Let redirect_hir be proc translate_redirection with child_ast
            proc list_append with redirects_list, redirect_hir
        Otherwise:
            Let arg_hir be proc translate_word with child_ast
            proc list_append with args_list, arg_hir
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_cmd, "arguments", args_list
    proc set_dict_value with hir_cmd, "redirections", redirects_list

    Return hir_cmd
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bash pipelines are sequences of commands joined by '|' where stdout of
each stage becomes stdin of the next. The HIR "pipeline" node holds the
ordered command list directly; the runtime semantics (forking processes,
wiring fds) are the responsibility of the target emitter since most
languages cannot model true pipe semantics inline.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_pipeline" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate pipeline to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 40

    Let hir_pipeline be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_pipeline, "node_type", "pipeline"

    Let commands_list be proc create_hir_list

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let cmd_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
        Let cmd_hir be proc translate_command with cmd_ast
        proc list_append with commands_list, cmd_hir
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_pipeline, "commands", commands_list

    Return hir_pipeline
End Process

@Reasoning:
The central dispatcher routes each AST node kind to its specialised
translator. Kinds 1-26 cover bash's structural and expansion nodes; the
51-53 range catches the atom kinds (word, string, number) via a single
range check rather than three separate If branches, which is the
v0.0.8.5 convention for contiguous tag ranges. Returning 0 for unknown
kinds is the silent-skip behaviour expected by the universal translator
when the bash parser is extended with new node types.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_node" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Main translation dispatcher

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 0

    Note: AST_SCRIPT (1)
    If node_type is equal to 1:
        Return proc translate_script with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_COMMAND (2)
    If node_type is equal to 2:
        Return proc translate_command with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_PIPELINE (3)
    If node_type is equal to 3:
        Return proc translate_pipeline with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_LIST (4)
    If node_type is equal to 4:
        Return proc translate_list with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_COMPOUND_COMMAND (5)
    If node_type is equal to 5:
        Return proc translate_compound_command with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_SUBSHELL (6)
    If node_type is equal to 6:
        Return proc translate_subshell with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_IF_STATEMENT (10)
    If node_type is equal to 10:
        Return proc translate_if_statement with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_WHILE_STATEMENT (11)
    If node_type is equal to 11:
        Return proc translate_while_statement with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_UNTIL_STATEMENT (12)
    If node_type is equal to 12:
        Return proc translate_until_statement with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_FOR_STATEMENT (13)
    If node_type is equal to 13:
        Return proc translate_for_statement with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_CASE_STATEMENT (14)
    If node_type is equal to 14:
        Return proc translate_case_statement with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_FUNCTION_DEFINITION (20)
    If node_type is equal to 20:
        Return proc translate_function_definition with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_VARIABLE_ASSIGNMENT (21)
    If node_type is equal to 21:
        Return proc translate_variable_assignment with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_VARIABLE (22)
    If node_type is equal to 22:
        Return proc translate_variable with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_COMMAND_SUBSTITUTION (26)
    If node_type is equal to 26:
        Return proc translate_command_substitution with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_ARITHMETIC_EXPANSION (24)
    If node_type is equal to 24:
        Return proc translate_arithmetic_expansion with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_PARAMETER_EXPANSION (25)
    If node_type is equal to 25:
        Return proc translate_parameter_expansion with ast
    End If

    Note: AST_WORD (51), AST_STRING (52), AST_NUMBER (53)
    If node_type is greater than or equal to 51:
        If node_type is less than or equal to 53:
            Return proc translate_word with ast
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
$(cmd) and `cmd` both lower to AST_COMMAND_SUBSTITUTION nodes whose
payload is the embedded command. We preserve the raw command text rather
than its substituted result because the HIR must round-trip back through
universal translation - the substitution is performed at the target
language's runtime, not at HIR construction time.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_command_substitution" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate command substitution to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 8

    Let hir_node be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "node_type", "command_substitution"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "command", value

    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
$((expr)) lowers to AST_ARITHMETIC_EXPANSION with the expression text
stored at offset 8. The HIR carries the expression verbatim because
bash's arithmetic grammar is C-like but the target may need to lower it
differently (e.g., to a let binding plus integer evaluation, or to a
target-specific eval call).
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_arithmetic_expansion" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate arithmetic expansion to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 8

    Let hir_node be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "node_type", "arithmetic_expansion"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "expression", value

    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bash parameter expansions ${var}, ${var:-default}, ${var#pattern},
${var/from/to} etc. carry rich semantics that not every target language
can express. The HIR stores the raw expansion text and a generic
"parameter_expansion" tag; backend-specific lowering decides whether to
emit a target-native equivalent or a fallback function call.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_parameter_expansion" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate parameter expansion to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 8

    Let hir_node be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "node_type", "parameter_expansion"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_node, "expansion", value

    Return hir_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bash command lists span the boolean composition operators (&&, ||) and
the sequence/background operators (;, &). The parser preserves each join
operator as an interleaved AST_LIST_OPERATOR marker node, so the AST_LIST
children alternate command, operator-marker, command, ... The HIR lowers
this into a "command_list" node carrying two parallel lists: "items"
(the command HIRs) and "operators" (the canonical operator spelling that
joins each adjacent command pair, one fewer entry than items). The target
emitter chooses how to map each composition to its language (e.g., && may
become an if-statement or a logical short-circuit), reading the operator
that precedes item i from operators[i-1].
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks the interleaved children. AST_LIST_OPERATOR markers (node type 7)
are not translated as commands; instead their value field (the operator
token type) is mapped to the canonical operator string ("&&", "||", ";",
"&") and appended to the "operators" list. Every other child is a command
translated via translate_node and appended to the "items" list. The
result is two parallel lists where operators[k] joins items[k] and
items[k+1].
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_list" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate command list (&&, ||, ;, &) to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 40

    Let hir_list be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_list, "node_type", "command_list"

    Let items be proc create_hir_list
    Let operators be proc create_hir_list

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
        Let child_kind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child_ast, 0

        If child_kind is equal to AST_LIST_OPERATOR:
            Let op_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child_ast, 8

            If op_token is equal to TOKEN_AMP_AMP:
                proc list_append with operators, "&&"
            Otherwise:
                If op_token is equal to TOKEN_PIPE_PIPE:
                    proc list_append with operators, "||"
                Otherwise:
                    If op_token is equal to TOKEN_AMP:
                        proc list_append with operators, "&"
                    Otherwise:
                        proc list_append with operators, ";"
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Let child_hir be proc translate_node with child_ast
            proc list_append with items, child_hir
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_list, "items", items
    proc set_dict_value with hir_list, "operators", operators

    Return hir_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bash compound commands { ...; } group statements without creating a
subshell - they share the parent's variable environment. The HIR
distinguishes compound_command from subshell so emitters can choose the
correct semantics (a JavaScript backend can emit a plain block; a Python
backend may need to wrap in a try/finally for trap propagation).
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_compound_command" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate compound command { commands; } to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 40

    Let hir_compound be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_compound, "node_type", "compound_command"

    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let body_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let body_hir be proc translate_node with body_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_compound, "body", body_hir
    End If

    Return hir_compound
End Process

@Reasoning:
Subshells (...) execute in a fresh process whose environment changes are
isolated from the parent. The HIR records the isolated execution intent
via the distinct "subshell" tag, allowing emitters to fork a child
process, spawn an isolated function call, or use language-specific
context managers as appropriate to the target.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_subshell" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate subshell ( commands ) to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 40

    Let hir_subshell be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_subshell, "node_type", "subshell"

    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let body_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let body_hir be proc translate_node with body_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_subshell, "body", body_hir
    End If

    Return hir_subshell
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bash if-statements always have a condition (child 0) and a then-body
(child 1); additional children represent elif/else branches in
declaration order. We expose the branches as a List so the emitter can
walk them sequentially, matching how bash itself evaluates them. The
field naming ("condition", "then_body", "branches") matches the canonical
HIR if-statement schema shared by all frontends.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_if_statement" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate if-then-else-fi to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 40

    Let hir_if be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_if, "node_type", "if_statement"

    Note: Condition (first child)
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let cond_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let cond_hir be proc translate_node with cond_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_if, "condition", cond_hir
    End If

    Note: Then body (second child)
    If child_count is greater than 1:
        Let then_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 8
        Let then_hir be proc translate_node with then_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_if, "then_body", then_hir
    End If

    Note: Elif/else branches (remaining children)
    If child_count is greater than 2:
        Let branches be proc create_hir_list

        Let i be 2
        While i is less than child_count:
            Let branch_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
            Let branch_hir be proc translate_node with branch_ast
            proc list_append with branches, branch_hir
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        proc set_dict_value with hir_if, "branches", branches
    End If

    Return hir_if
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bash while loops iterate while the condition command's exit status is
zero (success). The HIR captures this as a generic "while_loop" with
condition and body fields; the target emitter is responsible for the
exit-status-vs-boolean coercion if the destination language uses a
different truthiness model.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_while_statement" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate while-do-done to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 40

    Let hir_while be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_while, "node_type", "while_loop"

    Note: Condition
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let cond_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let cond_hir be proc translate_node with cond_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_while, "condition", cond_hir
    End If

    Note: Body
    If child_count is greater than 1:
        Let body_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 8
        Let body_hir be proc translate_node with body_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_while, "body", body_hir
    End If

    Return hir_while
End Process

@Reasoning:
Until loops are the inverse of while: they iterate while the condition's
exit status is non-zero (failure). We give them a distinct HIR
"until_loop" tag rather than rewriting to a while-with-negation because
preserving the source intent simplifies bidirectional translation and
matches what tools like shellcheck expect.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_until_statement" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate until-do-done to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 40

    Let hir_until be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_until, "node_type", "until_loop"

    Note: Condition
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let cond_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let cond_hir be proc translate_node with cond_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_until, "condition", cond_hir
    End If

    Note: Body
    If child_count is greater than 1:
        Let body_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 8
        Let body_hir be proc translate_node with body_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_until, "body", body_hir
    End If

    Return hir_until
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bash for-loops bind a variable to each word in a list. The translator
treats the last child as the body and every preceding child as a word
in the iterable - this matches the bash parser's layout. The loop
variable name itself lives in the AST node's value slot (offset 8) and
is copied directly into the HIR's "variable" field.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_for_statement" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate for-do-done to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 8
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 40

    Let hir_for be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_for, "node_type", "for_loop"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_for, "variable", value

    Note: Word list (all children except last)
    Let words be proc create_hir_list

    Let i be 0
    Let body_index be child_count minus 1

    While i is less than body_index:
        Let word_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
        Let word_hir be proc translate_word with word_ast
        proc list_append with words, word_hir
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_for, "words", words

    Note: Body (last child)
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let body_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, body_index multiplied by 8
        Let body_hir be proc translate_node with body_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_for, "body", body_hir
    End If

    Return hir_for
End Process

@Reasoning:
A case item is a "pattern[|pattern]) commands ;;" entry. The translator
treats the final child as the command body and every preceding child as
a pattern. Patterns flow through translate_word because they are
syntactically just words at the bash AST level - their glob semantics
are preserved verbatim for the target emitter to interpret.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_case_item" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate case pattern item to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 40

    Let hir_item be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_item, "node_type", "case_item"

    Note: Patterns (all children except last)
    Let patterns be proc create_hir_list

    Let i be 0
    Let commands_index be child_count minus 1

    While i is less than commands_index:
        Let pattern_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
        Let pattern_hir be proc translate_word with pattern_ast
        proc list_append with patterns, pattern_hir
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_item, "patterns", patterns

    Note: Commands (last child)
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let commands_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, commands_index multiplied by 8
        Let commands_hir be proc translate_node with commands_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_item, "commands", commands_hir
    End If

    Return hir_item
End Process

@Reasoning:
Case statements pair a scrutinee word (first child) with a list of case
items (remaining children). Splitting them into separate "word" and
"items" fields rather than treating them uniformly lets the emitter
preserve glob semantics on the scrutinee versus exact-match semantics on
each item's patterns. The items list is built via translate_case_item
which handles the per-arm pattern/body split.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_case_statement" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate case-in-esac to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 40

    Let hir_case be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_case, "node_type", "case_statement"

    Note: Word (first child)
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let word_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let word_hir be proc translate_word with word_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_case, "word", word_hir
    End If

    Note: Case items (remaining children)
    Let items be proc create_hir_list

    Let i be 1
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let item_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
        Let item_hir be proc translate_case_item with item_ast
        proc list_append with items, item_hir
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_case, "items", items

    Return hir_case
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bash functions have no formal parameter list - $1..$N positional
arguments are accessed by the body directly. So the HIR function node
only carries name and body fields, with the body lowered via
translate_node so any nested control flow inside the function is
processed by the same dispatcher.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_function_definition" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate function definition to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 8
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 40

    Let hir_func be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "node_type", "function_definition"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "name", value

    Note: Body
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let body_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let body_hir be proc translate_node with body_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "body", body_hir
    End If

    Return hir_func
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bash variable assignments (NAME=VALUE) bind the value to the variable
in the current shell scope. The HIR captures the name in the node's
value slot (offset 8) and the assigned expression in the first child;
target emitters render this as 'let' / 'var' / declaration as needed.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_variable_assignment" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate variable assignment to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 8
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 40

    Let hir_assign be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_assign, "node_type", "variable_assignment"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_assign, "variable", value

    Note: Value
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let value_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, 0
        Let value_hir be proc translate_node with value_ast
        proc set_dict_value with hir_assign, "value", value_hir
    End If

    Return hir_assign
End Process

@Reasoning:
The bash script root holds an ordered list of top-level statements. The
HIR "script" / "program" wrapper preserves the order so the target
emitter can produce a faithful linear output. The wrapping is necessary
even for single-statement scripts because the universal translator's
dispatcher expects a uniform root shape.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_script" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate script (top-level) to HIR

    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 32
    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 40

    Let hir_script be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_script, "node_type", "script"

    Let commands be proc create_hir_list

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let cmd_ast be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with children, i multiplied by 8
        Let cmd_hir be proc translate_node with cmd_ast
        proc list_append with commands, cmd_hir
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc set_dict_value with hir_script, "commands", commands

    Return hir_script
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single public entry point keeps the universal-translation pipeline
uniform: every frontend exposes one translate_<lang>_to_hir function so
the driver can dispatch without per-language knowledge. The actual
recursion is hidden behind translate_node, which performs tag-based
dispatch on Bash AST kinds; that internal split avoids leaking the
Bash-specific AST node types out to the orchestration layer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates the entire walk to translate_node, which is the polymorphic
Bash AST dispatcher built earlier in this file. ast is expected to be
the root Bash AST handle returned by bash_parser; translate_node reads
its type tag, fans out to the appropriate per-kind handler (command,
pipeline, function definition, if, while, case, etc.), and returns the
freshly allocated HIR hashtable representing the whole script. Caller
takes ownership of the returned HIR root and is responsible for
freeing it via the HIR destructor when downstream translation finishes.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_bash_to_hir" takes ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Main translation entry point

    @Reasoning:
    This is the main entry point for translating Bash AST to HIR.
    The HIR format uses dictionaries and lists to create a language-agnostic
    representation that can be translated to any other supported language.
    @End Reasoning

    Return proc translate_node with ast
End Process

Note: End of Bash→HIR Translator
